1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
https://slama.dev/comeback/

2
00:00:09,550 --> 00:00:10,150
Ozzak, this is Marcelka and I've asked her to manage things here from now on.

3
00:00:14,320 --> 00:00:15,280
Thank you, Tomas.

4
00:00:15,740 --> 00:00:19,820
I'd start by cleaning up, then we could repaint.

5
00:00:19,960 --> 00:00:21,320
How about pink?

6
00:00:22,560 --> 00:00:23,160
Me?

7
00:00:23,380 --> 00:00:23,540
Me.

8
00:00:23,750 --> 00:00:39,050
Then you'll wear your fabulous little suit with the pleather tie, and this sweetheart will wear a cream-white suit with this silk tie and lure customers by singing your greatest hits.

9
00:00:39,750 --> 00:00:49,950
You soak into me like rain and I'll soak into you, such happiness you won't find.

10
00:00:59,450 --> 00:01:05,850
Ozzak, this is Marcelka and I've asked her to help us get back on our feet starting today.

11
00:01:08,380 --> 00:01:09,720
I'm not singing anything!

12
00:01:09,960 --> 00:01:42,630
If anything does happen.

13
00:01:42,990 --> 00:01:46,610
Call, there's an extension line right up to our apartment.

14
00:01:46,710 --> 00:01:48,710
I don't think that'll be necessary.

15
00:01:49,750 --> 00:01:52,050
We'll find our way to each other, right?

16
00:01:52,210 --> 00:01:52,850
Sir?

17
00:01:52,850 --> 00:01:55,750
His friends call him Ozzak.

18
00:01:56,870 --> 00:01:57,510
Ozzak?

19
00:01:57,830 --> 00:01:58,470
Friends.

20
00:02:00,010 --> 00:02:02,850
Well then, let's get to it, friends.

21
00:02:03,250 --> 00:02:07,970
I'm off, I have a lot of things to do that I've been neglecting because of the shop.

22
00:02:09,990 --> 00:02:10,630
Right.

23
00:02:11,110 --> 00:02:11,750
Of course.

24
00:02:15,450 --> 00:02:16,900
So what should I call you?

25
00:02:17,250 --> 00:02:18,550
How about "boss"?

26
00:02:20,910 --> 00:02:23,590
I know you have your established system here.

27
00:02:23,670 --> 00:02:25,550
I don't want to disrupt it in any way.

28
00:02:25,850 --> 00:02:28,750
I'd just like to get acquainted with it.

29
00:02:29,250 --> 00:02:34,130
Look at the books so I know what sells and how.

30
00:02:34,130 --> 00:02:35,270
Music isn't a business.

31
00:02:36,650 --> 00:02:40,610
But you still sell something now and then, don't you?

32
00:02:40,610 --> 00:02:41,770
I need to start with that.

33
00:02:42,550 --> 00:02:44,050
Where's your ledger?

34
00:02:44,350 --> 00:02:45,950
All my accounting is over there.

35
00:02:49,350 --> 00:02:50,150
In the closet?

36
00:02:51,850 --> 00:02:52,410
Here.

37
00:02:54,050 --> 00:02:58,850
It only goes to May, we have narrow door frames.

38
00:03:02,250 --> 00:03:03,390
You have an error in the total here.

39
00:03:03,950 --> 00:03:04,750
That's a knot.

40
00:03:10,550 --> 00:03:13,150
Find someone who can handle Ozzak.

41
00:03:16,850 --> 00:03:17,570
Done.

42
00:03:19,150 --> 00:03:20,350
Handle the mail.

43
00:03:27,100 --> 00:03:27,820
Done.

44
00:03:30,950 --> 00:03:32,750
Stay hydrated.

45
00:03:38,150 --> 00:03:39,150
Done.

46
00:03:40,650 --> 00:03:43,150
Think through business strategy.

47
00:03:46,880 --> 00:03:47,760
Let's do this.

48
00:03:53,950 --> 00:03:58,610
Would you have any other souvenirs from Tomas's artistic career?

49
00:03:59,050 --> 00:04:01,250
Like the panties women used to throw at him?

50
00:04:01,750 --> 00:04:03,930
We won't attract anyone with underwear.

51
00:04:04,150 --> 00:04:05,350
That's what you think.

52
00:04:10,250 --> 00:04:11,650
Jesus, this one's mine.

53
00:04:11,850 --> 00:04:14,550
Sure, that was Susice in '87.

54
00:04:16,950 --> 00:04:17,350
We mainly need photos of Tomas.

55
00:04:20,850 --> 00:04:27,650
It needs to be obvious that a famous person owns this place.

56
00:04:31,550 --> 00:04:35,050
I destroyed all evidence of my brother's dark past long ago.

57
00:04:42,940 --> 00:04:44,220
Do you have an iron?

58
00:04:45,150 --> 00:04:45,650
Good day.

59
00:04:46,650 --> 00:04:47,150
Good day.

60
00:04:49,350 --> 00:04:53,880
I understand you have the complete Brutus discography.

61
00:04:54,050 --> 00:04:56,050
But of course, of course we do.

62
00:04:56,450 --> 00:04:57,950
I put it together myself.

63
00:04:58,450 --> 00:04:59,750
That's wonderful.

64
00:05:00,150 --> 00:05:01,850
Does it include "Slackers Go to Work"?

65
00:05:02,490 --> 00:05:03,830
I see you're a connoisseur.

66
00:05:03,870 --> 00:05:04,650
Of course it does.

67
00:05:05,350 --> 00:05:07,650
And what would you say to this?

68
00:05:09,620 --> 00:05:10,380
Concert, October 18th,

69
00:05:10,380 --> 00:05:12,820
1980, Rakovnik.

70
00:05:14,050 --> 00:05:16,750
That's the concert where the gymnasium burned down.

71
00:05:17,050 --> 00:05:19,250
I pulled it from the wreckage myself.

72
00:05:22,130 --> 00:05:23,610
Can I do anything else for you?

73
00:05:23,770 --> 00:05:25,050
Do you have the latest Chinaski?

74
00:05:25,170 --> 00:05:25,530
Yeah.

75
00:05:26,450 --> 00:05:32,450
Where did he go?

76
00:05:33,150 --> 00:05:34,150
My colleague went to get...

77
00:05:35,950 --> 00:05:36,780
A ribbon.

78
00:05:37,050 --> 00:05:39,950
And will he bring the Chinaski?

79
00:05:40,750 --> 00:05:41,850
Hard to say.

80
00:05:43,450 --> 00:05:45,450
The gentleman is waiting for the Chinaski.

81
00:05:46,350 --> 00:05:47,050
Screw off!

82
00:05:47,150 --> 00:05:53,050
Well, I'd better find them for you myself.

83
00:05:53,050 --> 00:05:54,030
Just a moment.

84
00:05:54,650 --> 00:05:56,210
Chinaski, we have them under...

85
00:05:56,210 --> 00:05:56,730
...

86
00:05:56,730 --> 00:05:57,430
Under...

87
00:05:56,730 --> 00:05:57,430
...

88
00:06:01,050 --> 00:06:02,250
Why are they under N?

89
00:06:02,550 --> 00:06:05,050
Well, as in "Nobodies."

90
00:06:06,990 --> 00:06:08,690
So that makes 329.

91
00:06:08,910 --> 00:06:09,810
And the Brutus stuff?

92
00:06:10,350 --> 00:06:11,350
They stay here!

93
00:06:11,820 --> 00:06:14,200
Someone who buys Chinaski has no right to them!

94
00:06:14,760 --> 00:06:16,400
But they're for my daughter!

95
00:06:16,950 --> 00:06:17,850
Even worse!

96
00:06:17,880 --> 00:06:19,100
Ruining your own child!

97
00:06:21,250 --> 00:06:24,000
You know what, I'll come back when your colleague calms down.

98
00:06:24,250 --> 00:06:26,050
I'm calm as a lamb!

99
00:06:28,450 --> 00:06:30,140
Then I'll come back when he changes his mind.

100
00:06:30,140 --> 00:06:32,080
I'm solid as a rock!

101
00:06:34,650 --> 00:06:36,750
When he's not here.

102
00:06:37,350 --> 00:06:38,370
I'm always here!

103
00:06:48,050 --> 00:06:50,520
I won't put up with it anymore, it's terrorism.

104
00:06:50,520 --> 00:06:52,320
Insecure old hag.

105
00:06:52,660 --> 00:06:55,240
Actually it's great that she gives you problems tailored just for you.

106
00:06:55,360 --> 00:06:56,160
Like this one.

107
00:06:56,750 --> 00:07:05,360
How long can a below-average singer stay home who earned five times the average salary during the communist era and put it in a two-percent foreign currency account?

108
00:07:05,550 --> 00:07:08,240
I already asked Mom what the average salary was under communism.

109
00:07:08,240 --> 00:07:08,980
So how much was it?

110
00:07:09,450 --> 00:07:10,250
Squat, she said.

111
00:07:10,350 --> 00:07:13,350
So two percent of five squats is how much?

112
00:07:14,550 --> 00:07:16,550
And what good will it do me when I figure it out?

113
00:07:17,950 --> 00:07:19,550
Dad, hello.

114
00:07:20,560 --> 00:07:21,060
Sweetie.

115
00:07:21,650 --> 00:07:22,450
You're home?

116
00:07:23,200 --> 00:07:23,700
Great.

117
00:07:24,450 --> 00:07:27,590
So you might be interested to know that your daughter is being bullied at school.

118
00:07:27,590 --> 00:07:28,590
Bullied how?

119
00:07:29,450 --> 00:07:30,250
Read this.

120
00:07:31,450 --> 00:07:40,800
How many unnecessary kilometers did a normalization-era pop star drive when she organized concerts at every collective farm that had a partnership with Soviet kolkhozes?

121
00:07:40,950 --> 00:07:42,350
A lot, actually.

122
00:07:42,750 --> 00:07:44,650
Do you know how many collective farms there were back then?

123
00:07:45,250 --> 00:07:48,500
Father, don't you realize why I have to calculate this?

124
00:07:48,500 --> 00:07:49,600
Well, it's obvious.

125
00:07:49,600 --> 00:07:52,450
To practice math, right?

126
00:07:52,480 --> 00:07:53,160
Read this.

127
00:07:54,550 --> 00:07:59,520
How many medals of labor did a below-average pop singer receive when he decided to participate in a youth festival in Havana?

128
00:08:01,650 --> 00:08:02,750
Well this, this is outrageous!

129
00:08:04,160 --> 00:08:07,760
I never got any medals, just a foreign currency voucher for a Yugo.

130
00:08:08,320 --> 00:08:09,740
What's a foreign currency voucher?

131
00:08:09,740 --> 00:08:10,680
What's a Yugo?

132
00:08:11,400 --> 00:08:12,580
Both are nothing.

133
00:08:13,050 --> 00:08:14,750
So what are we going to do about it?

134
00:08:15,050 --> 00:08:16,350
I'll go to the school.

135
00:08:20,950 --> 00:08:23,120
Or I'll write a letter.

136
00:08:23,550 --> 00:08:24,450
To the school, on paper.

137
00:08:26,250 --> 00:08:34,950
Dear Professor, please stop giving my daughter humiliating math assignments.

138
00:08:35,750 --> 00:08:40,750
If you have something against me personally, we'll settle it.

139
00:08:40,950 --> 00:08:43,250
Face to face, man to man.

140
00:08:45,250 --> 00:08:46,150
What's her name?

141
00:08:46,950 --> 00:08:47,750
Zborilova.

142
00:08:49,050 --> 00:08:50,050
The Comet?

143
00:08:50,050 --> 00:08:53,650
That hag is still alive?

144
00:08:54,550 --> 00:08:59,950
And she still slams students' heads against the blackboard?

145
00:09:00,550 --> 00:09:02,590
No, they banned that in the nineties, apparently.

146
00:09:02,590 --> 00:09:03,790
Now she just twists ears.

147
00:09:04,250 --> 00:09:06,180
That's nothing new.

148
00:09:06,650 --> 00:09:09,750
Why do you think Ozzak's left earlobe points up?

149
00:09:10,100 --> 00:09:11,300
She taught you too?

150
00:09:12,450 --> 00:09:14,070
So you know what's going on, and you'll help me.

151
00:09:14,070 --> 00:09:14,730
Sure I will.

152
00:09:15,850 --> 00:09:17,750
Of course I'll help you.

153
00:09:23,450 --> 00:09:26,750
How many unnecessary kilometers does a normalization-era pop star drive?

154
00:09:26,750 --> 00:09:28,810
Let's calculate the kilometers separately.

155
00:09:49,650 --> 00:09:51,070
Excuse me, I'd like to buy something.

156
00:09:51,070 --> 00:09:51,490
Buy?

157
00:09:52,150 --> 00:09:54,970
Go to my colleague, she knows everything about selling music.

158
00:09:54,970 --> 00:09:55,510
Thanks.

159
00:09:58,550 --> 00:10:00,400
Excuse me, madam, could you...

160
00:10:00,400 --> 00:10:01,660
I can't do anything.

161
00:10:02,350 --> 00:10:05,180
Nobody wants me here.

162
00:10:05,550 --> 00:10:07,350
Young man, nobody.

163
00:10:08,050 --> 00:10:09,100
You're a monster, sir.

164
00:10:09,100 --> 00:10:09,640
Me?

165
00:10:09,640 --> 00:10:11,740
I'm proud of it.

166
00:10:11,740 --> 00:10:14,100
With your pop, pop, pop.

167
00:10:14,260 --> 00:10:16,160
You'll drive this place into the ground.

168
00:10:16,650 --> 00:10:18,640
Artistic self-reflection.

169
00:10:18,640 --> 00:10:20,880
Incomprehensible to pop kitsch artists.

170
00:10:20,980 --> 00:10:22,600
Beer-hall primitivism.

171
00:10:23,650 --> 00:10:26,250
Would you buy something like this?

172
00:10:26,250 --> 00:10:26,550
Me?

173
00:10:27,080 --> 00:10:27,320
No.

174
00:10:27,480 --> 00:10:28,000
No?

175
00:10:28,180 --> 00:10:28,820
Then no!

176
00:10:29,160 --> 00:10:32,100
You'd rather have some stupid two-note ditty, right?

177
00:10:32,260 --> 00:10:32,580
No.

178
00:10:34,350 --> 00:10:36,350
I'd like to speak with your boss.

179
00:10:42,250 --> 00:10:43,650
You're all wimps.

180
00:10:44,450 --> 00:10:46,350
I'll go to Ozzak, he already sorted out the Comet.

181
00:10:46,750 --> 00:10:52,650
He didn't, they haven't lifted his school ban since 1988.

182
00:10:53,850 --> 00:10:55,050
I got twenty percent.

183
00:10:55,750 --> 00:10:57,220
Twenty percent, that's nonsense.

184
00:10:57,220 --> 00:10:58,140
Even Michal David didn't have that.

185
00:10:59,250 --> 00:11:02,150
Shouldn't we simplify it with the kolkhoz numbers?

186
00:11:02,440 --> 00:11:02,960
No.

187
00:11:03,020 --> 00:11:04,560
We should sign the letter.

188
00:11:04,720 --> 00:11:05,900
Sweetie, she straightened it out.

189
00:11:06,550 --> 00:11:09,550
Be glad you have both earlobes pointing down.

190
00:11:10,160 --> 00:11:11,980
Is the number of collective farms correct?

191
00:11:11,980 --> 00:11:17,140
Three hundred ninety-four, but a lot of them were called Red Dawn, and they get mixed up with state farms.

192
00:11:17,140 --> 00:11:18,240
It wasn't easy.

193
00:11:26,750 --> 00:11:27,350
Hello?

194
00:11:27,960 --> 00:11:28,500
What?

195
00:11:29,340 --> 00:11:30,140
And who?

196
00:11:31,950 --> 00:11:33,900
Hey, some strange man from the shop called.

197
00:11:34,250 --> 00:11:35,250
What did he say?

198
00:11:35,720 --> 00:11:36,260
Nothing.

199
00:11:36,850 --> 00:11:37,550
He's crying.

200
00:11:47,150 --> 00:11:49,830
I see you've started settling in here.

201
00:11:50,250 --> 00:11:52,150
So, where's the man who was crying?

202
00:11:52,650 --> 00:11:53,450
He drove him away.

203
00:11:53,950 --> 00:11:55,890
Dude, he wanted Madonna.

204
00:11:56,150 --> 00:11:57,430
She attracts those types.

205
00:11:57,430 --> 00:11:59,390
And he repels all customers.

206
00:11:59,450 --> 00:12:01,050
And without customers we'll go bankrupt.

207
00:12:02,150 --> 00:12:03,050
That's true.

208
00:12:03,850 --> 00:12:05,150
And what about our honor?

209
00:12:05,250 --> 00:12:08,050
Without that we'll go bankrupt too, and lose our ears on top of it.

210
00:12:08,150 --> 00:12:09,550
That's true.

211
00:12:09,640 --> 00:12:12,460
Man, you can't keep agreeing with everyone.

212
00:12:13,290 --> 00:12:13,850
That's true.

213
00:12:14,750 --> 00:12:20,050
Mr. Pacovsky, you have to decide: either we sell here or we preach.

214
00:12:20,050 --> 00:12:23,350
Well, definitely sell.

215
00:12:23,350 --> 00:12:23,870
Sell what?

216
00:12:24,350 --> 00:12:24,790
How?

217
00:12:24,790 --> 00:12:25,290
To whom?

218
00:12:25,290 --> 00:12:26,450
According to whom?

219
00:12:26,590 --> 00:12:28,590
And most importantly, don't say they're both right.

220
00:12:30,090 --> 00:12:32,310
Fine, fine, then each of you sell your own way.

221
00:12:34,750 --> 00:12:38,050
Whoever does better wins.

222
00:12:39,550 --> 00:12:41,770
I'm not going to compete with someone like that.

223
00:12:41,770 --> 00:12:42,570
Why not?

224
00:12:43,350 --> 00:12:46,050
Whoever sells more CDs by the end of the week wins.

225
00:12:48,590 --> 00:12:51,490
And whoever wins is right.

226
00:12:51,610 --> 00:12:54,610
And whoever is right becomes head of sales.

227
00:12:54,610 --> 00:12:58,450
And whoever becomes head of sales is the head of sales.

228
00:13:03,350 --> 00:13:17,030
Who wants to spin for a discount on the wheel of fortune?

229
00:13:18,050 --> 00:13:18,750
Go ahead.

230
00:13:18,750 --> 00:13:29,330
3 plus 1, that's wonderful, congratulations.

231
00:13:29,530 --> 00:13:30,550
And what does that mean?

232
00:13:30,790 --> 00:13:32,970
This beautiful prize means that...

233
00:13:33,350 --> 00:13:37,650
When you buy a collection of three romantic synthesizer CDs, you get one Dara Rolins free.

234
00:13:40,870 --> 00:13:42,230
Three hundred crowns, please.

235
00:13:42,890 --> 00:13:43,530
Thank you.

236
00:13:46,650 --> 00:13:48,700
Next, next, next, next.

237
00:13:49,150 --> 00:13:52,150
Who else wants to try their luck?

238
00:13:53,650 --> 00:13:54,780
Lexa, buy a CD.

239
00:13:55,250 --> 00:13:56,450
I already bought three.

240
00:13:56,610 --> 00:13:57,510
Is that all you've got?

241
00:13:59,150 --> 00:14:00,390
Let's do it the same way she does.

242
00:14:00,390 --> 00:14:01,490
Like her, never.

243
00:14:01,490 --> 00:14:03,090
But we'll do it like her.

244
00:14:03,650 --> 00:14:04,450
But our way.

245
00:14:18,820 --> 00:14:19,360
Thanks.

246
00:14:20,850 --> 00:14:22,850
Come back tomorrow, there'll be new pieces.

247
00:14:24,050 --> 00:14:25,450
Wow Lexa, that was an idea.

248
00:14:25,850 --> 00:14:27,850
Beer with a CD for a buck.

249
00:14:37,350 --> 00:14:39,100
So what's for dinner tonight?

250
00:14:40,450 --> 00:14:40,950
I'm starving.

251
00:14:47,950 --> 00:14:50,650
Schnitzel, 20 minutes before serving.

252
00:14:53,250 --> 00:14:57,050
And this is what the letter to the Comet looks like before someone signs it.

253
00:14:57,850 --> 00:14:59,450
Sign and there'll be schnitzel.

254
00:14:59,550 --> 00:15:02,950
I also have mashed potatoes hidden somewhere you'll never find.

255
00:15:04,350 --> 00:15:05,380
That's blackmail.

256
00:15:05,550 --> 00:15:07,650
No, no, no, that's the principle of cooperation.

257
00:15:07,650 --> 00:15:09,950
I help you and you help me.

258
00:15:09,950 --> 00:15:10,710
Cooperation?

259
00:15:10,710 --> 00:15:12,610
They tried to force that on me 20 years ago.

260
00:15:12,630 --> 00:15:13,910
I didn't sign then either.

261
00:15:14,090 --> 00:15:15,950
No signature, no schnitzel.

262
00:15:16,850 --> 00:15:18,050
Little girl, back then they sent me to a peace song festival in Ulaanbaatar as punishment, and I survived that too.

263
00:15:23,570 --> 00:15:26,530
Fine, then now you'll be surviving on crackers.

264
00:15:26,910 --> 00:15:31,050
Sweetie, you're not going to stop cooking just because of some stupid math problems.

265
00:15:32,650 --> 00:15:34,550
You have five minutes to think about it.

266
00:15:42,630 --> 00:15:43,890
Good day, Marcelka.

267
00:15:43,890 --> 00:15:46,750
I just stopped by to see if you need anything.

268
00:15:47,650 --> 00:15:48,550
Can you make schnitzel?

269
00:15:49,750 --> 00:15:50,750
Of course.

270
00:15:51,330 --> 00:15:52,090
Great.

271
00:15:54,450 --> 00:15:57,250
And where would you hide mashed potatoes here so I wouldn't find them?

272
00:15:58,350 --> 00:15:59,150
In the oven.

273
00:16:01,090 --> 00:16:01,790
Yep.

274
00:16:11,190 --> 00:16:12,330
So how are you?

275
00:16:13,950 --> 00:16:16,450
Excellent, Marcelka, excellent.

276
00:16:16,750 --> 00:16:18,550
Like divine cooking.

277
00:16:20,720 --> 00:16:22,000
You'll regret this.

278
00:16:24,950 --> 00:16:27,930
Tomas, I'd need a little favor from you.

279
00:16:28,150 --> 00:16:28,850
What kind?

280
00:16:29,350 --> 00:16:33,650
I had this promotional idea, but I'd need you for it.

281
00:16:33,850 --> 00:16:34,850
Anything, then.

282
00:16:35,350 --> 00:16:37,250
An autograph signing session with Tomy Pacsy.

283
00:16:38,250 --> 00:16:39,450
The ladies will come flocking.

284
00:16:40,550 --> 00:16:41,550
Never.

285
00:16:45,550 --> 00:16:46,150
What should I wear?

286
00:16:59,850 --> 00:17:01,750
No, no, no, that won't work.

287
00:17:04,410 --> 00:17:05,870
This won't do, Tomas.

288
00:17:06,090 --> 00:17:08,870
It's too tight on you.

289
00:17:09,250 --> 00:17:11,310
Wait, let me work with it.

290
00:17:11,720 --> 00:17:12,260
And who are you?

291
00:17:12,440 --> 00:17:13,460
Alright, alright, come.

292
00:17:15,360 --> 00:17:15,860
Hi.

293
00:17:16,650 --> 00:17:17,440
What's going on here?

294
00:17:17,750 --> 00:17:18,450
No comment.

295
00:17:20,230 --> 00:17:20,850
Again?

296
00:17:20,850 --> 00:17:21,950
You maybe, once more.

297
00:17:23,990 --> 00:17:25,390
Hey, it pinched.

298
00:17:28,450 --> 00:17:29,550
Bro, someone might come in.

299
00:17:29,630 --> 00:17:31,690
Take her downstairs to the basement, like we always do.

300
00:17:32,710 --> 00:17:33,210
What?

301
00:17:34,150 --> 00:17:35,350
Like I always do.

302
00:17:36,450 --> 00:17:37,160
Sure.

303
00:17:37,160 --> 00:17:39,050
One more time, okay?

304
00:17:39,130 --> 00:17:39,770
Again.

305
00:17:41,850 --> 00:17:44,150
And I'm done, I'm done.

306
00:17:47,350 --> 00:17:47,950
Good day.

307
00:17:52,850 --> 00:17:56,350
Dude, bro, you betrayed me.

308
00:17:57,350 --> 00:17:58,100
What's wrong?

309
00:17:58,650 --> 00:18:01,250
You want to keep eating raw meat?

310
00:18:06,850 --> 00:18:07,750
Yeah, I don't know.

311
00:18:10,250 --> 00:18:11,950
Sasha, you look great.

312
00:18:13,050 --> 00:18:15,350
Around forty, husband left you, IQ about seventy.

313
00:18:18,450 --> 00:18:20,350
Yeah, typical fan of my father.

314
00:18:21,230 --> 00:18:22,530
Isn't this a scam?

315
00:18:23,650 --> 00:18:25,450
Look, everyone else signs autographs but not me.

316
00:18:26,750 --> 00:18:30,350
Look, I'll fold this over and he'll sign right here.

317
00:18:31,550 --> 00:18:33,550
Sasha, five minutes.

318
00:18:33,950 --> 00:18:37,350
And this amazing clipboard is yours.

319
00:18:38,250 --> 00:18:39,950
I just don't know what to say.

320
00:18:41,250 --> 00:18:42,550
Just imagine.

321
00:18:42,580 --> 00:18:44,220
I know, it won't be easy.

322
00:18:44,260 --> 00:18:45,520
Imagine that Dad is your idol.

323
00:18:46,600 --> 00:18:48,400
But he's not that ugly a guy.

324
00:18:50,850 --> 00:18:51,950
Sasha, great.

325
00:18:52,460 --> 00:18:53,700
You're starting to lose it.

326
00:18:59,350 --> 00:19:00,950
How I loved you.

327
00:19:01,350 --> 00:19:04,190
Can you imagine, I even wanted to marry you.

328
00:19:04,550 --> 00:19:08,950
You were simply my entire youth.

329
00:19:09,450 --> 00:19:18,050
You fancy little show-off.

330
00:19:19,250 --> 00:19:21,250
What could that bimbo be selling them?

331
00:19:21,950 --> 00:19:24,850
Bro's last record was a vinyl in '88.

332
00:19:25,250 --> 00:19:30,650
The Pacsy album is sold out, but I have Helena Vondráčková.

333
00:19:31,020 --> 00:19:32,780
She's his friend.

334
00:19:34,000 --> 00:19:35,940
That's not fair, she's cheating.

335
00:19:38,750 --> 00:19:41,550
If she can, we can too.

336
00:19:56,450 --> 00:19:57,330
Mr. Pa...

337
00:19:57,330 --> 00:20:00,810
Maestro, can you sign for me?

338
00:20:00,810 --> 00:20:01,750
Of course, my pleasure.

339
00:20:02,850 --> 00:20:04,350
You know my songs?

340
00:20:04,650 --> 00:20:06,350
Of course, everyone knows them.

341
00:20:06,850 --> 00:20:07,350
Really?

342
00:20:07,850 --> 00:20:10,350
My grandma used to play them for me at bedtime when I was little.

343
00:20:10,450 --> 00:20:11,010
Really?

344
00:20:11,750 --> 00:20:12,350
Really.

345
00:20:13,150 --> 00:20:15,550
Actually, I still fall asleep to them.

346
00:20:16,950 --> 00:20:19,950
So the two of us basically sleep together.

347
00:20:20,850 --> 00:20:23,050
Yeah, I only sleep with you.

348
00:20:24,450 --> 00:20:26,700
In that case, maybe we could sometime...

349
00:20:26,700 --> 00:20:27,980
Dad, don't hold things up.

350
00:20:29,050 --> 00:20:30,350
Of course, pardon, right.

351
00:20:31,840 --> 00:20:32,820
Thank you, maestro.

352
00:20:32,900 --> 00:20:35,340
And if you ever feel lonely...

353
00:20:35,480 --> 00:20:36,040
Next.

354
00:20:39,450 --> 00:20:41,460
I only wanted his autograph, not his underwear.

355
00:20:41,950 --> 00:20:43,250
It just happened on its own.

356
00:20:45,090 --> 00:20:45,650
Ladies!

357
00:20:46,110 --> 00:20:50,910
May I draw your attention to our sale: Eighties with an Eighty.

358
00:20:50,910 --> 00:20:58,190
We're offering an eighty percent discount on all eighties music, so if you'd like any CD...

359
00:20:58,190 --> 00:20:59,250
We already have one.

360
00:20:59,830 --> 00:21:01,170
You already have one?

361
00:21:01,210 --> 00:21:01,930
CD, CD.

362
00:21:03,170 --> 00:21:04,670
Where did you get it?

363
00:21:04,670 --> 00:21:05,310
Over there.

364
00:21:09,650 --> 00:21:13,550
And how come the sleeve has no picture and nothing written on it?

365
00:21:13,710 --> 00:21:15,150
It's the white album, madam.

366
00:21:15,490 --> 00:21:16,430
An absolute rarity.

367
00:21:20,570 --> 00:21:22,470
But it's Led Zeppelin inside.

368
00:21:22,470 --> 00:21:25,310
I don't care what's inside.

369
00:21:25,450 --> 00:21:28,450
As long as he... he signs it for me.

370
00:21:36,450 --> 00:21:38,150
So you have the same number of marks.

371
00:21:39,290 --> 00:21:39,810
Sure?

372
00:21:39,870 --> 00:21:40,310
You've.

373
00:21:40,950 --> 00:21:43,510
So the winner over the Bimbo is...

374
00:21:43,650 --> 00:21:46,250
What winner?

375
00:21:46,250 --> 00:21:48,290
Tomas, that's some kind of nonsense.

376
00:21:48,290 --> 00:21:49,490
Are you sure?

377
00:21:49,770 --> 00:21:51,450
Yes, I counted it myself.

378
00:21:51,670 --> 00:21:53,570
I wouldn't rely too much on that.

379
00:21:54,850 --> 00:21:56,840
Jesus, good day, Professor.

380
00:21:56,840 --> 00:21:57,360
Pacovsky!

381
00:21:57,520 --> 00:21:58,040
No!

382
00:21:58,040 --> 00:22:00,350
Not you, Pacovsky.

383
00:22:03,550 --> 00:22:12,450
I always took you for a sly one who hides in the shadows, sails with the current, and pushes his retarded brother in front of him.

384
00:22:12,650 --> 00:22:16,550
And with this you truly surprised me.

385
00:22:17,750 --> 00:22:22,750
If you have something against me personally, we'll settle it face to face, man to math teacher.

386
00:22:25,280 --> 00:22:27,320
There's even a provocation at the end here.

387
00:22:27,480 --> 00:22:31,880
Come by tonight, I'll show you paradise, with love, Tomy Pacsy.

388
00:22:34,150 --> 00:22:43,750
When I saw you clowning around in Ein Kessel Buntes, I was sure I was right about you, but this letter made me take an interest in you again.

389
00:22:43,780 --> 00:22:45,420
Well, I'm glad, so.

390
00:22:45,660 --> 00:22:50,020
A colleague bought your latest CD yesterday, the white album.

391
00:22:50,880 --> 00:22:52,860
We listened to it in the staff room and...

392
00:22:54,350 --> 00:22:59,150
Pacovsky, have you gone deeper?

393
00:22:59,250 --> 00:23:02,250
There's authenticity in that music, passion, feeling, and the range, you know, that kind of...

394
00:23:02,450 --> 00:23:16,950
It was absolutely gorgeous.

395
00:23:16,950 --> 00:23:19,750
But that's Led Zeppelin, that's Robert Plant singing, not me.

396
00:23:22,040 --> 00:23:22,560
What?

397
00:23:22,820 --> 00:23:29,080
And the letter is also a mix-up, I wrote it, well actually I didn't really write it, so it's a misunderstanding.

398
00:23:33,350 --> 00:23:35,350
Look, you really, I swear, you won't believe this, but I really can't help it, okay?

399
00:23:35,950 --> 00:23:38,550
It's my brother's fault.

400
00:23:41,040 --> 00:23:41,560
Pacovsky.

401
00:23:43,150 --> 00:23:45,450
No, Comrade Teacher!

402
00:23:55,460 --> 00:23:57,540
And it's back down again, as it should be.

403
00:23:57,640 --> 00:23:58,060
Great.

404
00:24:01,550 --> 00:24:07,360
So again, how much did the Pacovsky brothers earn from fraudulent CD sales?

405
00:24:07,360 --> 00:24:08,340
I've got it.

406
00:24:09,250 --> 00:24:14,950
Marcelka sold at a discount and Ozzak didn't give change for meal vouchers, so he's actually ahead by three CDs.

407
00:24:18,550 --> 00:24:22,350
But I got two black eyes because of him, so call it one.

408
00:24:27,980 --> 00:24:28,940
I'm still the boss.

409
00:24:29,040 --> 00:24:29,800
I'm the boss.

410
00:24:29,880 --> 00:24:30,880
I'm the boss!

411
00:24:36,150 --> 00:24:39,950
Ah, schnitzel, smells good, nice and crispy.

412
00:24:40,550 --> 00:24:43,250
Well, that's worth at least one mark.

413
00:25:00,750 --> 00:25:03,650
Ozzak, I've decided who'll be head of sales.

414
00:25:05,250 --> 00:25:06,050
It'll be you.

415
00:25:06,850 --> 00:25:08,450
Because you deserve it.

416
00:25:09,550 --> 00:25:10,650
Well, excellent.

417
00:25:11,250 --> 00:25:14,050
Mr. Ozzak, from now on I will only listen to metal.

418
00:25:15,740 --> 00:25:16,300
Correct.

419
00:25:16,560 --> 00:25:18,440
And I'll be quiet the entire workday.

420
00:25:18,480 --> 00:25:19,840
And I'll fetch your beer.

421
00:25:21,650 --> 00:25:23,250
Bimbo, I must be dreaming.

422
00:25:26,350 --> 00:25:27,450
I really must be dreaming.

423
00:25:28,250 --> 00:25:28,750
Well then, well then.

424
00:25:30,550 --> 00:25:31,600
Bimbo, go fetch some beer.

425
00:25:31,850 --> 00:25:32,820
And quick, before I wake up.

426
00:25:32,820 --> 00:25:33,120
Chop, chop.

427
00:25:33,280 --> 00:25:34,130
Yeah, yeah.

428
00:25:35,750 --> 00:25:39,550
Bro, hang up your gold record.

429
00:25:40,050 --> 00:25:40,810
Yeah, yeah.

430
00:25:47,350 --> 00:25:51,650
Sweetie, bring me meatballs, or no, roast a duck and bring it down to the shop.

431
00:25:57,140 --> 00:25:57,480
Something.

432
00:26:08,850 --> 00:26:09,950
Never, never.
